The continental margin off Mauritania is marked by the presence of the most southern deep-water coral mounds known in the eastern North Atlantic, comprising
Lophelia pertusa (
Linnaeus, 1758
)
and
Madrepora oculata (
Linnaeus, 1758
)
. These represent one of the largest coral-mound provinces, with a latitudinal extent exceeding 200 km (
Colman et al . 2005
;
Westphal et al . 2007
). The mound province extends from north of the Cap Timiris Canyon System (
Krastel et al . 2004
) to the Mauritanian Slide Complex in the south (
Wien et al . 2007
). Coral mounds occur at depths between 450 and 550 m , in the lower and less-depleted part of a pronounced oxygenminimum zone, caused by one of the largest upwelling systems worldwide (
Hagen 2001
), making the waters off Mauritania highly productive (
Gabric et al . 1993
;
Marañón & Holligan 1999
). The living corals form small, isolated colonies, only infrequently forming larger aggregations, and most often colonising canyon walls or isolated rock outcrops. Bryozoans seem to appear in great diversity and abundance in these coral habitats (
Westphal et al . 2012
).

Bryozoan specimens were retrieved from surface-sediment samples collected during RV Maria S. Merian cruise MSM 16 / 3 “PHAETON – Paleoceanographic and paleoclimatic record on the Mauritanian shelf” (
13 October – 20 November 2010
) off Mauritania (
Westphal et al . 2012
). Sampling was performed by using a box corer with an opening of 50 × 50 cm and a height of 55 cm , a grab sampler, and a remotely operated vehicle (ROV) (Sperre SubFighter 7500 DC of The Tjärnö Centre for Underwater Documentation, Sven Lovén Centre for Marine Sciences Tjärnö, University of Gothenburg, Strömstad, Sweden ). A total of 25 coral-rubble samples, partly with living coral specimens still present, were screened for bryozoans using a Zeiss Stemi 2000 stereomicroscope, revealing about 60 species. The two new cheilostome species, present in 13 out of the 25 coral rubble samples, were selected for the micro-CT analysis. These 13 samples were representative of the highly variable seafloor topography in the area investigated, comprising coral mounds, canyons and positions in between, which allowed an assessment of habitat preferences (
Fig. 1
,
Table 1
).

Measurements obtained from SEM images and micro-CT datasets were statistically evaluated using PAST 3.06 (
Hammer et al . 2001
). Normal distribution was tested using the Shapiro-Wilk test. Welchs’s t-test, which returns robust results even if the variances of the samples are unequal, was used to test the equality of means. Significance level was set at 0.05 .

