Acquisition of morphological data in bryozoans—SEM vs microcomputed tomography analyses. The current methodological standard in describing bryozoan species with a calcified skeleton is the employment of SEM. This method results in high-resolution images of even the tiniest structures, and modern devices do not require a conductive specimen surface, i.e. coating of specimens. Because the SEM is based upon the emission of nearsurface electrons, visualising internal skeletal structures requires complete or partial destruction. To address this problem, serial thin sections have been commonly utilized, fragmenting a specimen into single slices, which has proven to be especially useful for Paleozoic
Bryozoa (
Wyse Jackson & McKinney 2013
)
. However, resolution is limited by the thickness of the sections. For the complete spatial visualisation of internal cavities, resin casts have proven to be very useful, but require dissolution of the entire specimen (e.g.
Wiesemann 1960
;
Voigt 1968
;
Voigt & Williams 1973
). Partial or complete loss of specimens has likely hampered using the structure and shape of internal cavities for the taxonomic description of species, although
Voigt & Williams ( 1973 )
highlighted the value of these characters.

Faulwetter et al . ( 2013 )
discussed the application of micro-CT as a component of the growing field of cybertaxonomy, which is based on virtual taxonomic material, using polychaetes as an example. The most crucial requirements for establishing volumetric datasets, and for providing more than just additional data in taxonomic research, are the standardisation of file types and the introduction of adequate repositories and handling policies (
Rowe & Frank 2011
). The International Code of Zoological Nomenclature might eventually have to implement rules regarding the handling and systematic value of such virtual type-relevant material, possibly leading to the introduction of the so-called ‘cybertype’, which is considered by some authors as a new kind of type specimen (
Faulwetter et al . 2013
;
Godfray 2007
). These types are simultaneously accessible to multiple researchers in different places, without the necessity of handling the original physical specimen, leading to increased speed in taxonomic research. However, such virtual type material cannot replace physical specimens, as only the original specimen carries all information and any virtualisation is a mere copy with reduced information content. It is also not desirable to base species descriptions solely on characters requiring complex and time-consuming equipment or destruction of specimens. ‘Cybertypes’ should be considered only as a standardised way to represent type specimens and distribute taxonomic data, but not as replacements for physical specimens.

Environmental preferences of the new bryozoan species. Both new species belong to relatively speciose genera with global distributions, ranging from tropical to polar waters, and representatives of both genera are known from adjacent regions south and north of the area we investigated ( Canu & Bassler 1925 , 1928 ; Cook 1968 , 1985 ;
Aristegui & Cruz 1986
). Despite the lower frequency of occurrence of
S. imragueni
n. sp.
, both species appear to have generally similar habitat preferences, living specimens occurring on mound tops, mound flanks, in canyons and on canyon shoulders (
Table 1
;
Fig. 1
). Temperatures ranged from 9 to 12 ° C, salinity from 35.2 to 35.5 psu, and oxygen concentration from 0.92 ml l - 1 to 1.54 ml l - 1 . The first two parameters are in the normal range for bryozoans, especially in light of the global distribution of both genera. Oxygen saturation, however, was remarkably low, and close to dysoxic levels (
Rhoads & Morse 1971
;
Levin 2003
). As bryozoans lack any dedicated respiratory organs, oxygen uptake is relatively ineffective and takes place via simple diffusion (
Ryland 1967
). Bryozoans are active filter feeders with low metabolic costs in general, although there are considerable interspecific differences in oxygen consumption, representing fundamentally different metabolic strategies in different species (
Peck & Barnes 2004
). Lophophore activity, i.e. feeding, consumes only a minor amount of energy, while most energy appears to be used for growth, reproduction and polypide regeneration (
Peck & Barnes 2004
). Colonies of
C. bafouri
n. sp.
frequently bore fertile zooids, and
S. imragueni
exhibited strong secondary calcification, both of which can be considered to be highly energy-demanding. Thus, adaptation to low oxygen concentrations is evident. A possible way in which these species reduce their energy consumption might be slow growth. Intracellular digestion by the bryozoan gut is also quite ineffective (
Dewel et al . 2002
), necessitating a high supply of food particles (
Taylor 2000
). This high nutritional demand is met in waters off Mauritania by increased primary productivity resulting from the strong upwelling regime. Food particles are exported from surface waters to greater depths, thus reducing the energy required to satisfy the bryozoans’ nutritional demands, because less oxygen is required to capture the same quantity of food.
